snippet: Corrections appearing in print on January 23, 2013.
Senator Charles E. Schumer blamed Hurricane Sandy for the absence of Brooklyn’s sweetest product at the Inaugural Luncheon, but beekeepers in Red Hook dispute their hives were ruined.
abstract: New York Sen Charles E Schumer, serving as master of ceremonies for traditional Inaugural Luncheon, said Brooklyn honey was absent from menu because Hurricane Sandy had wiped out hives but beekeepers in Red Hook dispute their hives were ruined.

headline.main: Honey From Red Hook Was Missing, and So Was the Right Reason
headline.print_headline: Honey From Red Hook Was Missing, and So Was the Right Reason

snippet: Texas Instruments and A.M.D. see uncertain demand and a widespread customer reluctance to order until the last minute.
abstract: Chip makers Texas Instruments and Advanced Micro Devices post quarterly results that top analysts’ estimates, but warn of rocky period ahead as mobile devices gain traction with consumers at expense of personal computers; Texas Instruments says its fourth-quarter profit fell to $264 million, or 23 cents a share, from $298 million or 25 cents a share, year earlier; Advanced Micro Devices says it lost $473 million, of 63 cents a share, in quarter.

headline.main: Chip Makers Forecast a Slowdown in Orders
headline.print_headline: Chip Makers Forecast A Slowdown In Orders

snippet: A new self-storage facility, with customer-friendly extras, has opened on Manhattan’s West Side, but analysts said the city remains underserved.
abstract: Gotham Mini Storage, new self-storage facility with customer-friendly extras, opens on Manhattan’s West Side, but industry analysts say city remains underserved.

snippet: Reports last week suggested that people might finally be tired of Apple's iPhone, citing sources that said sales were weaker than expected. But the latest numbers do not support that conclusion.
abstract: Reports last week suggested that people might finally be tired of Apple's iPhone, citing sources that said sales were weaker than expected. But the latest numbers do not support that conclusion.

headline.main: Are iPhone Sales Waning? The Numbers Don't Say So

snippet: While Google’s most lucrative business, search on desktop computers, is slowing, the search giant has not yet figured out how to make equivalent profits on mobile devices.
abstract: Google reports fourth-quarter revenue of $14.42 billion, increase of 36 percent over year-ago quarter; net income rose 7 percent to $2.89 billion, or $8.62 a share; while Google’s most lucrative business, search on desktop computers, is slowing, search giant has not yet figured out how to make equivalent profits on mobile devices.

headline.main: Google Still in a Struggle With Mobile
headline.print_headline: Google Still In a Struggle With Mobile

snippet: Even though revenue rose and customers increased, the phone company reported a loss of $4.22 billion, more than double the loss a year ago.
abstract: Verizon Communications reports fourth-quarter loss of $4.22 billion, or $1.48 a share, more than double the loss a year ago; damage from Hurricane Sandy cost 7 cents a share, and pension charges reduced earnings by $1.55 a share; revenue climbed to $30.05 billion, 5.7 percent increase from year ago, and slightly higher than estimates.

headline.main: Storm and Pension Costs Leave Verizon With Bigger Quarterly Loss
headline.print_headline: Storm and Pension Costs Leave Verizon With Bigger Quarterly Loss

snippet: The chief executive of TSMC, one of the biggest semiconductor makers in the world, hinted at big orders to come, fueling the Apple rumor mill that the iPhone maker may soon shift its chip production to the Taiwanese company.

headline.main: TSMC Anticipates Big Orders. Is Apple One of Them?

snippet: Consumers are buying more LEDs, but over time, the long-lasting bulbs will result in fewer sales, making the race for market share all the more urgent.
abstract: LEDs, or light-emitting diodes, are projected to outsell incandescent light bulbs in North America by 2014; prices for energy efficient LEDs are higher than incandescent bulbs but are falling steadily; long-lasting bulbs will result in fewer sales over time, making race for market share urgent.

headline.main: LEDs Emerge as a Popular ‘Green’ Lighting
